e pink-and-blue striped receiving blankets used to swaddle newborns, to the development of sex-specific nutrition plans based on societal expectations of the stature of children, a gendered culture permeates pediatrics and children’s health throughout the twentieth and early twenty-first centuries. This book provides a look at how gender has served as one of the frameworks for pediatric care in the U.S. since the specialty’s inception. Pink and Blue deploys gender—often in concert with class and race—as the central critical lens for understanding the function of pediatrics as a cultural and social project in modern U.S. history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aChildrenxHealth and hygienezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aGender identity in childrenzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPediatricsxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPediatricszUnited StatesxPsychological aspectsxHistory. 0aSex differences (Psychology) in childrenzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSex role in childrenzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh  ahealth, medicine, newborns, public health, babies, blankets, baby blankets, swaddles, sex-specific nutrition plans, nutrition plans, children, gender roles, gender, pediatric care, U.S., United States, race, class, medical care, pediatrics, pediatric transgender medicine, HPV, neonatal intensive care, NICU, Doctor-Parent Communication, down syndrome, Mid-Twentieth Century, boys, girls, raising children, mom, dad, mother, father, family, childhood, 1950s Pediatric Endocrinology, Pediatric Endocrinology, Body Politic, vaccine, childhood vaccine, Masculinity, puberty, Competitive Youth Sports, weight, height, HPV Vaccination, birth, infant, pregnancy.1 aBachynski, Kathleen E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConis, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://